author: hftquant_
text:
üñ•Ô∏èüìêRemember, when stock-bond correlation goes from negative to positive, overall portfolio volatility will generally go up. üöÄAnd vice versa. When correlation goes negative, overall portfolio volatility will generally go down. In the last week, stock bond correlations have dropped tremendously, which explains the big vol crush ü©∏ we have witnessed. 
The current structure of seasonal equity flows and how they relate to what is occurring in the bond market in my opinion is more relevant than anything else out there in terms of where price wants to likely move to here. Throughout the past couple weeks, I have been mentioning that one thing to really keep an eye on at this juncture is how the market responds to the now anticipated 1 potential rate cuts that is being priced into 2025. A major drop off üö®from the initial 5 last year, of course.
Additionally, it looks as if the market again has limited interest in hedge protection. 
Even if it may be recognized as a more optimal time to hedge ü¶î  books. Hedges out there have not been marked this cheap for a very long time. Again, with $VIX at such levels, not surprising. Specifically, vol is low, that it looks to be a case where it has never been easier to strengthen the book üìï against risks. I think it is also important to segway here and touch up on something we have not talked about much as of late. Being that throughout history, over the last 30 years, markets actually began their significant decline after the Fed began to aggressively cut rates, as opposed to before. ü§î 
The underlying thought process and logic here seems to stem from the notion that once a recession occurs, rate cuts occur out of ‚Äúurgency.‚Äù Which in turn leads $SPX lower.¬†üîë 
Additionally, if the initial rate cut does NOT follow a recession, the market is usually higher üöÄ on every timeframe following. There was no yield curve steepening in 1984, 89, 95, or 98. Yet, yield curve inversion and steepening happened in 1973, 79, 81, 01, and 08. üîë One thing to acknowledge may be that the market is not currently falling because of the initially planned five anticipated rate cuts ‚úÇÔ∏è which began for 2024. Rather, the Fed will generally cut rates in response to the economy contracting first. 
Which is when the yield ‚ö†Ô∏è curve will generally steepen thereafter. üé¢ 
With all this said, timing an optimal short for a market top may be heavily revolved around not just the big upcoming FOMC option flow setup, but also around whether the Fed even cuts at all this year. ‚òùüèΩIn other words, continuing to monitor the yield curve to see whether it presumes more steepening, to bring us to the initial (and maybe only 2024) Fed cut. I think the real question the market should be asking is whether we get rate cuts, with a soft landing and no recession thereafter. üí° In my opinion, that would be the only ultimate recipe for much higher üü¢ equity prices in 2024. 
Any other result, primarily being the market being way ahead of itself here on even 1 cut (i.e. as in no cuts happen), could actually turn out to be somewhat disastrous ü©∏for the $SPX, given it is trading near all time highs again, and stretched valuations. 
Believe it or not, the margin for error is that small now, because of this scenario alone. Some food ü•ò for thought üí≠ here, as we head into FOMC next week.üéß

author: hftquant_
text:
üñ•Ô∏èüìêIn my opinion, there is no doubt that when volatility picks up, ability to trade in & out of ODTE calls/puts entices sentiment. ‚òùüèΩSimply due to fast reversion possibilities. Fast alpha.¬† However, within the past few weeks, its not the case for options traders. Or any types of traders for that matter. Vol has been absolutely smashed, and if this does persist, trading short dated options becomes IMMENSELY more difficult. üîë 
ü§î Also, rumors that only retail is surrounding ODTE options in particular, is definitely false. Data shows multiple types of participants interested in these new instruments. Including wealth advisors, vol hedge funds, and event driven asset managers. ‚ú®Additionally, it is becoming apparent that in terms of time of day, most ODTE activity looks to be stemming from within the first hour of the open, on the slightly out of the money strikes. Specifically, 1% for OTM calls, & 2% for OTM puts. ‚ô†Ô∏èOn days where futures tend to gap open down hard, seems ODTE vol sellers continue to immediately jump in & smash üí• premium. Not only does this mess with the market attempting to find a meaningful intraday trend, it destroys ODTE theta decay. ü©∏ 
The reality though is that those trying to consistently hit the OTM calls and puts >= 1% OTM are actually getting wrecked. Furthermore, to think that hedging risk with ODTE as opposed to $VIX is gaining popularity is also false. Not the way to hedge risk. 
üö®Since most traded ODTE contracts seem to be >= 1% OTM, obviously based on option dynamics, this will lead to heavy delta/gamma and theta risk. Shorter-term options such as ODTE, carry heavy gamma, which is why the swings are so furious as we near expo. Here is the caveat. Data shows overwhelming majorities in general trading $SPX on a more short-dated basis. As opposed to more longer-term. In my opinion, tells you market conditions now make it no longer worthwhile to buy/short & hold anything overnight. üîë 
This is big, because if appetite for overall risk is shifting to shorter term (i.e. too much risk for longer term buy/hold strategies), then the way one needs to perceive how to trade this market efficiently will shift with it. Looks like that has now begun. So what is the best course? üßê 
Of course, with that, there is much more. Such as what strikes are the optimal strikes to hit on each of these entries? How far in or how far out of the money does one go? That is always the hardest part, being able to optimize the strikes. Can maybe drop a follow up thread in future on this subject, as there is a lot to take in mathematically. 
‚úÖ But for starters, as mentioned in beginning of the thread, I do not think going out of the money (OTM) on the strikes is the way to play. Personally, I never go OTM when trading ODTE. Calls or puts. I prefer trading them in the money (ITM). In other words, I am willing to pay more for the option to take on the theta profile of an in the money ODTE call/put, as opposed to an OTM one. Why? ü§® Well forgetting about the data already mentioned supporting that trading ODTE OTM at say > =1% from current market price has not shown to be optimal based on backtests performed, I like to have more flexibility with the theta attached. üï∂Ô∏è 
Particularly given that with ODTE, the theta & gamma profiles are juiced up within the first 2 hours of open, and the tail end 1 hour into close. Basically, you hit nicely, or you zero out in theory on the premium as end of day expo arrives. Everything must be done fast. Not much time to think when in it. When in an ODTE, notice how the trading days seem to basically end in what seems to be only 2-3 hours. That is that whole idea of time against you that causes this ‚è∞. Theta decay that is. When we are in on any intraday trading position (i.e. 0DTE, 1DTE, etc.), time is our enemy. Always remember that. I guess that is what makes it so intense though. ‚ô†Ô∏è

author: KevinLMak
text:
Some thoughts on $PGY

1) Over the past 6 months I've spoken with Mike Kurlander in person and on zoom calls at length about the business. He's very knowledgeable, has a deep background in capital markets, and from my perspective was an asset to the business.

2) His sudden departure is definitely unsettling. It goes against best practices of how these types of transitions "should" happen. (i.e. Give a few months notice, ideally find a successor first, and publicly announce a transition period of a few months so investors see it's all planned).

3) The things to read into is the fact that the CFO knows the most (with the CEO) about the company's past and future. If the future was exceptionally bright, (barring exceptional personal circumstances: sick wife/kid/etc.) it doesn't particularly make financial sense to resign. Unless the opportunity that presents itself is that much better.

4) In terms of the company's past, their financials are pretty great, with growing revenues and growing adjusted EBITDA, etc. He has signed off on all those financials, so he's not resigning to get away from that- because it doesn't really work that way. So I'd say we can rule out historical fraud type of scenarios. (this is more of an issue when a new CFO comes in, and suddenly resigns when they see the mess that they've been dropped into, they leave to not be attached to the fraudulent behavior).

5) In terms of the company's future: It's really hard to see Mike having exceptionally clairvoyant insight into the future numbers. Not because he doesn't know what he's doing, but because of the nature of their business. They're growing their current partner relationships, and they're also signing new partners. USBank probably doesn't know whether they will ramp from XXm to $2B or not, Mike certainly doesn't. The market (fed rates, defaults, recession, etc) is going to do what it does, and Mike (or anyone else) can't realistically predict that. If they were building some sort of ticking-time bomb of defaults with their AI, honestly, I don't think Mike would know/see that because it would be obscured by the AI until the actual numbers started to materialize (and they haven't, according to the ABS and default reports).

6) I'll also note that it appears Mike wasn't particularly generously compensated, as he only had ~1M shares and $1M cash comp. I think for a company like Pagaya, although they don't have a lot of cash to pay their execs, he should have had a deeper equity grant to keep him incentivized (you want him to make $20m+ if the stock goes to $5. In the current framework he'd only make about $3M).

7) So while this as a whole, in my mind, reflects negatively on the company and its valuation- I will remind others that these types of situations are not binary. Without Mike their chance of success is lower than with Mike (but maybe they find a better successor and that changes). It also means we should be keeping a closer eye on the next 2 quarters of filings to see whether things have suddenly turned for some reason, or whether things are "business as usual".

8) I mentioned that the CTO sold 1.5M shares today, which does raise some eyebrows, but this was a 10b5-1 sale and as disclosed, was initiated/planned on 8/24/2023 (i.e. He signed paperwork on that date saying "sell my shares on 11/24/2023"). So the timing is just.. really really bad? for like, two reasons: (1) You NEVER want to sell a chunk of executive shares on the least liquid trading day of the year (Friday of Thanksgiving), and (2) it coincided with the CFO's departure. Some times you just get two flat tires on the same day.

https://t.co/bYPawiPm4E

9) Curious to see where Mike lands next, it may provide a bit of insight into what just happened, and it wouldn't surprise me if we find out in the next 6-8 weeks.

I'll add more as I percolate some other thoughts and follow some other leads.

I have always been in the camp rate cut's are bullish AS LONG AS it is while beating inflation and not because something is broke.  There is historical evidence that the market crashes every time a cut is done due to something breaking.  I believe that is Unemployment.  Out of all of the data we have gotten over the last month that makes everyone believe the rate cut is for the right reason. Unemployment's large spike is what I believe really caused the FED pivot. Anytime in all of history when we experience this type of curvature for the length of time it get's increasingly out of hand. 

Now let's look at the market with psychology. IF we ignored the unemployment data and looked at all other data collectively this would fit the soft-landing narrative and appear the rate cut is for "beating inflation" which should be extremely bullish.  IF this is the case the entire market should be going absolutely crazy. 80% of stocks in the market are down 80% from their ATH's...  stocks like this should be risk on and be 50% off of their recent lows. INSTEAD we have major names near their "BLACK MONDAY" lows.  This is including $BTC & $ETH.

This is not the sign of risk on and very much the opposite and what looks like distribution into all the retail who believes the market is bullish. 

Now technicals...   Practically ever major name has bearish divergences on the larger time frame with MACD correction indicators like giving up the 50 weekly RSI on names like $AMD $GOOG $AMZN $MSFT who hold the stock market up.  This is also while the rest of the market is continuing to break down.

author: laurenbalik
text:
$ZETA's Disqus is on many websites but it's deadweight on most. Extreme longtail distribution. Most websites it's on are just honeypots anyway, or fake websites, or sites with little-to-no traffic.

$ZETA's best use cases are selling audiences of the biggest morons possible to their clients selling supplemental insurance, weird financial products, etc.

"Political revenue" is not the right way to think about it.

Disqus on political websites is acquisition.

All the biggest morons make comment section accounts after they get triggered or want to argue with people, they then get profiled by Disqus, then Disqus (Zeta) sells these on the other side of the business to supplemental insurance/weird financial product clients.

Think about it: if you have people betting on dumb political spreads (low financial literacy) and arguing about politics (respond emotionally to stimuli) these are great audience builder tools for selling dumb financial products, annuities, supplemental life insurance, etc...or at least they are good in the short term.

You only need good profiles on a low millions number of people, even if you have weak profiles on hundreds of millions.

$ZETA is completely bubbled around this election and their narrative around financially engineering their stock price for their 2025 plan. They don't have a plan through 2025.
